<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-295-118  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 295 118.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  June 1989 v7 n6 p66(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A HyperCard for the PC: Apple's HyperCard has been cloned for thePC in the form of (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Goodman, Danny.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Brightbill-Roberts and Co Ltd's $99.95 HyperPAD, an AppleHyperCARD clone, is a menu- and prompt-driven, object-orientedapplication environment that allows non-programmers to createapplications easily.andP;  HyperPAD is completely character-based andcan not produce graphics.andP;  It runs on 8088 machines with only 384Kof RAM.andP;  HyperPAD is very capable of creating simple accountspayable-receivable applications, electronic Rolodexes, to-dolists, calendars and schedules, time and billing programs, andcustom DOS shells for launching applications.andP;  The product isscheduled for release in Apr 1989 for a list price of $99.95.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Brightbill-Roberts and Company Ltd. (product introduction).andO;Product:   HyperPad (Data base management system).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersProduct IntroductionSoftware PackagesProgramming SupportApplications Programming.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   Product information. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>